Don’t fall victim of thinking it’s the sharpness of a photo that makes a sale! Sharpness May be less that 1% ( if that) of what makes a photo marketable or makes a sale. 

It’s so interesting to see many fall victim in placing so much effort and focus in details that in the end aren’t significant or don’t  really translate in making a sale or a solid print which is marketable. I think often it’s the story sold by the “fix it up chappie” people listen to. 

EXAMPLE 
Painfully …. I shot this photo at 3200 ISO as years ago I forgot to change camera settings after shooting the Aurora all night long. It’s soft, not tack sharp, and overall technically not a great edit for large wall hangers. Yet it continuse to sell exceptionally well, even large prints up to 84 inches. Yes I cringe ….. yet in the end it’s the colors, the mood, the composition, the scene, the content that matters to clients. Only other photographers can see the lacking detail at shows and events. 

There’s many things regarding sharpening that simply don’t translate into the production of a print. Clients simply don’t zoom in at 1000% when viewing their fine art on a large wall. 

 I do believe sharpness is one element that one should be part if an effective workflow,  just don’t fall victim in thinking that it’s everything or significant. 

We’ll cover more details as to what really matters at next years Print Sales Masterclass. Reach out for more details.

I always chuckle this time of the year as “Photo Competitions” are everywhere and seem to claim a desire to showcase "the best". Aside from pulling at the ego in all of us and thrill to compete, we often fail to realize the true intentions of most of these "competitions" 

Photo "competitions" are mostly a business strategy that puts a business in front of a new audience, motivates one to share one's work ( at the expense of the participant ) for someone else's benefit, and typically gives the organizing business an SEO boost. 

Don’t be fooled YOU ARE THEIR FREE MARKETING MACHINE! 

Is it really a platform and showcase you and your art? Or is it entirely something else? Usually it's the latter.... 

While some competitions are free to enter, some cost upwards of $15 to $50 an entry. Some competitions I see boast of 10,000-20,000 entries... Profitable Business?....... Well you do the math. 

What about these "free photo contests" ? Well if you win …..some say you can be included in their Calendar.... Free exposure ? …or is it a way the Calendar can have beautiful imagery AT NO COST and a free marketing vehicle ( YOU) to market the business riding on the excitement of each contest participant eager to share share share?! 

Photo contests ARE NOT altruistic. Very few photo contests are run by non-profit organizations solely for promoting photography as an art form, instead, they’re most often done for some kind of financial benefit or business marketing boost. It’s not really about sharing your work. One well known pano photo “competition” deems 45% of the entries as a winner with their Gold, Silver, Bronz tiers…. 

Whether one likes to compete in a game or not.... the largest question remains..... in a world of subjectivity...can there ever really be something defined as "The Best" ? 

Don't be fooled, theres deeper reasons behind photo “competitions”. Its Big Business. Think twice before you let go of your edited files, Raw Files, photo rights and read the fine print!

There’s often a reason the Worlds most regarded photographers aren’t entering their images in photo competitions. What say you?

Last year's trip seemed to be the trip of rainbows, and this year it seemed it was the Sea Turtle 

Protection is what he sea turtle symbolizes. Seeing a sea turtle means that you have a guardian spirit watching over you. The Honu is a symbol of both wisdom and good luck. As the only native reptile to Hawaii, they are considered to be an Aumakua, or guardian spirit. 

These awesome creatures are significant animal to Hawaiian culture. The legend shares they were the original guides showing the ancient Polynesians the way to get to the Hawaiian islands. As they migrate through the tropical waters they swim great distances .

These creatures are over 150 million years old, and so it is fair to respect their experience and ability to survive while so many other animals have come and gone, and humanity is just a flash in time in comparison.

 It's important to give these protected and sacred creature distance as they crawl ashore. Taking this image at a distance with a 400 mm telephoto lens allowed for capturing it's amazing detail as though we were close.

Living LARCH in the Canadian Rockies! 🍁The beauty of larch trees in the fall is truly captivating. As the temperatures start to drop in the Canadian Rockies, the needles of the larch trees undergo a remarkable transformation. They change from their usual vibrant green to brilliant shades of gold and yellow, creating a stunning contrast against the backdrop of the evergreen forests.

This transformation is quite incredible, especially when combined with the golden hues of aspen, birch, and poplar leaves that are also found in the region. The landscape becomes a kaleidoscope of warm, autumnal colors. 

The golden larch needles create a magical atmosphere, and when the sunlight filters through the trees, it bathes the forest floor in a warm, enchanting glow. It's a definitely an intensely beautiful scene in the fall.
